Normality Test

Sushank Pokhrel (Homepage)

Assessing whether a dataset follows a normal distribution is a crucial step in statistical analysis.

1. Loading Required Libraries

You need to install the libraries (or packages) before theyre available in R. For that use the function install.packages().

4. Visualizing the Data Distribution

Using Density Plots

Density plots are used to understand the distribution of numerical variables.

ggplot() +
  geom_density(
    data = dummy_data,
    aes(x = data1),
    fill = "grey"
  )
## Warning: Removed 477 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_density()`).

  • ggplot() Initializes the plotting object using the ggplot2 package.
  • geom_density() Creates a density plot for the specified data.
  • aes(x = data1): Maps the data1 column to the x-axis.
  • fill = "grey": Fills the density plot with a grey color for better visualization.

The density plot here is somehow normally distributed as it shows bell shaped curve.


Repeating for Other Columns

You can create density plots for other variables in the dataset:

# Density plot for data2
ggplot() +
  geom_density(
    data = dummy_data,
    aes(x = data2),
    fill = "grey"
  )


# Density plot for data3
ggplot() +
  geom_density(
    data = dummy_data,
    aes(x = data3),
    fill = "grey"
  )
## Warning: Removed 300 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_density()`).


Assessing Normality with Q-Q Plots

qqnorm(dummy_data$data1)
qqline(dummy_data$data1, col = "red")

qqnorm(dummy_data$data2)
qqline(dummy_data$data2, col = "red")

qqnorm(dummy_data$data3)
qqline(dummy_data$data3, col = "red")

  • qqnorm(): Creates the Q-Q plot for a dataset.
  • qqline(): Adds a reference line to the Q-Q plot, indicating perfect normality. Deviations from this line suggest departures from normality.


Q-Q (Quantile-Quantile) plots are used to assess whether the data follows a normal distribution. A straight diagonal line suggests normality.

Using ggplot2 package for developing Q-Q plots.

Q-Q plot for data1

ggplot(dummy_data, aes(sample = data1)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red")
## Warning: Removed 477 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_qq()`).
## Warning: Removed 477 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_qq_line()`).


Q-Q plot for data2

ggplot(dummy_data, aes(sample = data2)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red")


Q-Q plot for data3

ggplot(dummy_data, aes(sample = data3)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red")
## Warning: Removed 300 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_qq()`).
## Warning: Removed 300 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_qq_line()`).

  • aes(sample = data1):Specifies the column to analyze (data1).
  • stat_qq(): Creates the Q-Q plot by comparing the quantiles of the data to a theoretical normal distribution.
  • stat_qq_line(): Adds a reference line to the Q-Q plot. If the points lie on or near the line, the data is approximately normally distributed.


5. Formal Tests for Normality

Shapiro-Wilk Test

The Shapiro-Wilk test is a widely used method for testing normality. It examines whether a dataset significantly deviates from a normal distribution.

Test for data1

shapiro.test(dummy_data$data1)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data1
## W = 0.99782, p-value = 0.1992


Test for data2

shapiro.test(dummy_data$data2)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data2
## W = 0.99889, p-value = 0.4874


Test for data3

shapiro.test(dummy_data$data3)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data3
## W = 0.99938, p-value = 0.9742
  • The null hypothesis (H): The data follows a normal distribution.
  • If p < 0.05: Reject the null hypothesis (the data is not normal).
  • If p 0.05: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (the data is approximately normal).
  • The closer the test statistic is to 1, the closer the data is to normality.


Anderson-Darling Normality Test

The Anderson-Darling test is another formal method for testing normality, often more sensitive to deviations in the tails of the distribution.

You need the package nortest for this test.

library(nortest) # you need to install the this package if not installed previously.

ad.test(dummy_data$data1)
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data1
## A = 0.65992, p-value = 0.08472
ad.test(dummy_data$data2)
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data2
## A = 0.32739, p-value = 0.5185
ad.test(dummy_data$data3)
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data$data3
## A = 0.25286, p-value = 0.7347
  • If p < 0.05: The data is not normal.
  • If p 0.05: The data is approximately normal.



Normality Tests on Long-Format Data

When data is structured in a long format (e.g., one column for variable names and another for corresponding values, normality tests must be conducted separately for each group (variable). This requires filtering data for each variable to test normality independently.

1. Loading the Excel File.

# Load the long-format data
dummy_data_long <- readxl::read_excel(
  "D:/Drive/r_training/Datasets/dummy_data.xlsx",
  sheet = "Sheet2"
) |> na.omit() # Remove NA values


2. Inspect the data structure

head(dummy_data_long)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   variable values
##   <chr>     <dbl>
## 1 data3     -0.89
## 2 data3      4.04
## 3 data3      5.32
## 4 data3      6.84
## 5 data3      8.62
## 6 data3      8.8
str(dummy_data_long)
## tibble [3,706  2] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)
##  $ variable: chr [1:3706] "data3" "data3" "data3" "data3" ...
##  $ values  : num [1:3706] -0.89 4.04 5.32 6.84 8.62 ...
##  - attr(*, "na.action")= 'omit' Named int [1:17] 111 307 443 780 998 1368 1579 1798 2018 2049 ...
##   ..- attr(*, "names")= chr [1:17] "111" "307" "443" "780" ...


3. Confirm there are no missing values

sum(is.na(dummy_data_long))
## [1] 0

There are none.


4. Filtering Data & Performing normality test

Using dplyr::filter() to Extract Data

# Extract data for 'data1'
data1 <- dummy_data_long |>
  dplyr::filter(variable == "data1")


Verify the unique group name

unique(data1$variable)  # Output: "data1"
## [1] "data1"


Performing Shapiro-Wilk Test for Normality

shapiro.test(data1$values)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  data1$values
## W = 0.99782, p-value = 0.2022


Using Base R to Filter Data

# Extract data for 'data2'
data2 <- dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data2", ]


Perform the Shapiro-Wilk test

shapiro.test(data2$values)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  data2$values
## W = 0.9989, p-value = 0.4975


5. Testing Without Extracting Subsets

Normality tests can be performed directly on specific subsets without creating intermediate variables. It can be quite tricky.

Data in must be in vector format for normality testing.

Directly using base function to extract the dataset and checking its class.

# Check the class of the subsetted column
dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"] |> class()
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

It is a table data frame, or simply data frame. Therefore, we cant perform the test in it, as it needs to be a numeric vector.


Converting it into a numeric vector

# Convert to a vector using `[[1]]`
dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"][[1]] |> class()
## [1] "numeric"

It is a numeric vector.


Alternatively, we can use the function pull() from dplyr package for converting it into a numeric vector

# Convert to a vector using `pull()`
dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"] |>
  dplyr::pull(values) |> class()
## [1] "numeric"

It is also a numeric vector.


Perform the Shapiro-Wilk test directly in the numeric vector.

shapiro.test(
  dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"][[1]]
)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"][[1]]
## W = 0.99938, p-value = 0.9741


OR using pull() function from the dplyr package.

shapiro.test(
  dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"] |>
    dplyr::pull(values)
)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dplyr::pull(dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"], values)
## W = 0.99938, p-value = 0.9741


Alternatively,

  dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"] |>
  dplyr::pull(values) |>
  shapiro.test()
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dplyr::pull(dummy_data_long[dummy_data_long$variable == "data3", "values"], values)
## W = 0.99938, p-value = 0.9741



Normality testing with the other dataset.

1. Loading and Exploring the Data

The dataset contains electricity utility rates across various states in the U.S. The goal is to compare the commercial rates (comm_rate) among selected states.

# Load the dataset
electricity <- readxl::read_excel(
  "D:/Drive/r_training/Datasets/electricity_utility_rates.xlsx",
  sheet = "sheet1"
)

# Inspect the structure of the dataset

The dataset contains utility rates for 50 states. For simplicity, we select four states: AZ, MI, IA, and VA.


2. Filtering the Data

# Filter data for selected states
elec_filt <- electricity |>
  dplyr::filter(
    state %in% c("AZ", "MI", "IA", "VA")
  )


3. Visualizing the Data

Density Plot

Density plot for all selected states

ggplot(
  data = elec_filt,
  aes(x = comm_rate, fill = state)
) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Commercial Rates by State",
       x = "Commercial Rate",
       y = "Density")


Density Plots for Each State

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "AZ", ], aes(x = comm_rate)) +
  geom_density(fill = "pink") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for AZ")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "MI", ], aes(x = comm_rate)) +
  geom_density(fill = "pink") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for MI")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "IA", ], aes(x = comm_rate)) +
  geom_density(fill = "pink") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for IA")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "VA", ], aes(x = comm_rate)) +
  geom_density(fill = "pink") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for VA")


4. Testing for Normality


Quantile-Quantile (QQ) Plot

QQ plot for each state

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "AZ", ], aes(sample = comm_rate)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "QQ Plot for AZ")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "MI", ], aes(sample = comm_rate)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "QQ Plot for MI")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "IA", ], aes(sample = comm_rate)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "QQ Plot for IA")

ggplot(data = elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "VA", ], aes(sample = comm_rate)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "QQ Plot for VA")


Shapiro-Wilk Test
# Perform the test directly for each states. 
shapiro.test(elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "AZ", "comm_rate"][[1]])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "AZ", "comm_rate"][[1]]
## W = 0.61595, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "MI", "comm_rate"][[1]])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "MI", "comm_rate"][[1]]
## W = 0.77735, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "IA", "comm_rate"][[1]])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "IA", "comm_rate"][[1]]
## W = 0.63302, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "VA", "comm_rate"][[1]])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  elec_filt[elec_filt$state == "VA", "comm_rate"][[1]]
## W = 0.71293, p-value < 2.2e-16
